<paragraph id="8BB1020BFFE0FFB7D5FF3F8868487DC9" blockId="8.[160,807,1477,1503]" box="[160,807,1477,1503]" pageId="8" pageNumber="657">
<heading id="D0F9B567FFE0FFB7D5FF3F8868487DC9" bold="true" box="[160,807,1477,1503]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="8" pageNumber="657" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B97ADE19FFE0FFB7D5FF3F8868487DC9" bold="true" box="[160,807,1477,1503]" pageId="8" pageNumber="657">
<taxonomicName id="4C0E7988FFE0FFB7D5FF3F886AD37DC9" baseAuthorityName="Germar" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[160,444,1477,1503]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Ceratozygum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="657" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horridum">
<emphasis id="B97ADE19FFE0FFB7D5FF3F886AD37DC9" bold="true" box="[160,444,1477,1503]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="657">Ceratozygum horridum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rarity or lack of knowledge?
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB1020BFFE0FFB6D5FF3FB7687D7943" blockId="8.[160,1155,1530,1728]" lastBlockId="9.[160,1156,142,618]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="658" pageId="8" pageNumber="657">
The Wallacean shortfall – the geographic distribution of most species is incomplete and poorly described at all scales (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE0FFB7D4AD3C5069F37E20" author="Lomolino MV" box="[498,668,1565,1590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="657" pagination="293 - 296" refId="ref7636" refString="Lomolino MV. 2004. Conservation Biogeography. In: Lomolino MV, Heaney LR, editors. Frontiers of biogeography: new directions in the geography of nature. Sunderland (MA): Sinauer Associates, Inc; p. 293 - 296." type="book chapter" year="2004">Lomolino 2004</bibRefCitation>
) – is a critical gap for different branches of biology. It is substantial in many biomes and ecoregions of the Neotropics, such as Amazon (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE0FFB7D4513C2F6AB47E6D" author="Hortal J &amp; de Bello F &amp; Diniz-Filho JAF &amp; Lewinsohn TM &amp; Lobo JM &amp; Ladle RJ" box="[270,475,1634,1659]" pageId="8" pageNumber="657" pagination="523 - 549" refId="ref7141" refString="Hortal J, de Bello F, Diniz-Filho JAF, Lewinsohn TM, Lobo JM, Ladle RJ. 2015. Seven shortfalls that beset large-scale knowledge of biodiversity. Annu Rev Ecol Evol Syst. 46: 523 - 549. doi: 10.1146 / annurev-ecolsys- 112414 - 054400." type="journal article" year="2015">Hortal et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
), the dry diagonal (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE0FFB7D79A3C2F68C07E6D" author="Werneck FP &amp; Gamble T &amp; Colli GR &amp; Rodrigues MT &amp; Sites JW Jr." box="[709,943,1634,1659]" pageId="8" pageNumber="657" pagination="3014 - 3034" refId="ref9078" refString="Werneck FP, Gamble T, Colli GR, Rodrigues MT, Sites JW Jr. 2012. Deep diversification and long-term persistence in the South American ' dry diagonal': integrating continent-wide phylogeography and distribution modelling of geckos. Evolution. 66: 3014 - 3034. doi: 10.1111 / j. 1558 - 5646.2012.01682. x." type="journal article" year="2012">Werneck et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
), and even in the political unities (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE0FFB7D4033CC8694B7E88" author="Hortal J &amp; de Bello F &amp; Diniz-Filho JAF &amp; Lewinsohn TM &amp; Lobo JM &amp; Ladle RJ" box="[348,548,1669,1694]" pageId="8" pageNumber="657" pagination="523 - 549" refId="ref7141" refString="Hortal J, de Bello F, Diniz-Filho JAF, Lewinsohn TM, Lobo JM, Ladle RJ. 2015. Seven shortfalls that beset large-scale knowledge of biodiversity. Annu Rev Ecol Evol Syst. 46: 523 - 549. doi: 10.1146 / annurev-ecolsys- 112414 - 054400." type="journal article" year="2015">Hortal et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
), which may comprise heterogeneous landscapes. In 
<collectingCountry id="F319429BFFE0FFB7D5FF3CEA6B837ED6" box="[160,236,1703,1728]" name="Bolivia" pageId="8" pageNumber="657">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, where 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E7988FFE0FFB7D41A3CEA6AA87ED6" baseAuthorityName="Germar" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[325,455,1703,1728]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Ceratozygum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="657" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horridum">
<emphasis id="B97ADE19FFE0FFB7D41A3CEA6AA87ED6" box="[325,455,1703,1728]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="657">C. horridum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded for the first time, in two different ecoregions, the fauna of arthropods is poorly known (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE1FFB6D7313AC3680178B1" author="Perger R &amp; Grossi P" box="[622,878,142,167]" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref8335" refString="Perger R, Grossi P. 2013. Revision of the rhinoceros beetle genus Oryctophileurus Kolbe with description of a new species, the male of O. varicosus Prell, and notes on biogeography (Scarabaeoidea, Dynastinae, Phileurini). ZooKeys. 346: 1 - 16. doi: 10.3897 / zookeys. 346.6114." type="journal article" year="2013">Perger and Grossi 2013</bibRefCitation>
; Perger 2015; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE1FFB6D1563AC36A4178DC" author="Perger R &amp; Guerra F" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" pagination="143 - 149" refId="ref8394" refString="Perger R, Guerra F. 2015. The first longhorned beetle record for the Prepuna in the Bolivian Andes and Potosi Department in Bolivia: a new species of Dirocoremia (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae: Rhopalophorini). Zootaxa. 4052 (1): 143 - 149. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4052.1.9." type="journal article" year="2015">Perger and Guerra 2015</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE1FFB6D4603AFC6A1978DC" author="Perger R &amp; Guerra F" box="[319,374,177,202]" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" pagination="277 - 284" refId="ref8452" refString="Perger R, Guerra F. 2016. The description of a new calyptrate fly mimicking species of the fungus weevil genus Gymnognathus Schonherr 1826 from the southern Bolivian Andes (Coleoptera: Anthribidae: Anthribinae). Zootaxa. 4084 (2): 277 - 284. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4084.2.7." type="journal article" year="2016">2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE1FFB6D4D83AFC69B478DC" author="Perger R &amp; Santos-Silva A" box="[391,731,177,202]" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" pagination="375 - 380" refId="ref8509" refString="Perger R, Santos-Silva A. 2018. A true long horn - a new species of Macronemus Dejean, 1835 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae, Acanthoderini) from the Bolivian Andes. Zootaxa. 4471 (2): 375 - 380. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4471.2.10." type="journal article" year="2018">Perger and Santos-Silva 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The lack of information about the regional fauna hinders the access to parameters used to quantify biodiversity and then compromises the understanding of the biogeography, macroecology and conservation in different scales (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE1FFB6D40A3B5469497924" author="Oliveira U &amp; Paglia AP &amp; Brescovit AD &amp; de Carvalho CJB &amp; Silva DP &amp; Rezende DT &amp; Leite FSF &amp; Batista JAN &amp; Barbosa JPPP &amp; Stehmann JR" box="[341,550,281,306]" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" pagination="1232 - 1244" refId="ref8050" refString="Oliveira U, Paglia AP, Brescovit AD, de Carvalho CJB, Silva DP, Rezende DT, Leite FSF, Batista JAN, Barbosa JPPP, Stehmann JR, et al. 2016. The strong influence of collection bias on biodiversity knowledge shortfalls of Brazilian terrestrial biodiversity. Diversity Distrib. 22: 1232 - 1244. doi: 10.1111 / ddi. 12489." type="journal article" year="2016">Oliveira et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). The SDMs hint priority areas to samplings of specific taxa, boosting filling the gaps on distributional records.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3145180FFE1FFB6D59F3B13695E7A7C" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB1020BFFE1FFB6D59F3B13695E7A7C" blockId="9.[160,1156,142,618]" pageId="9" pageNumber="658">
The cyrtocorines are not commonly found neither in nature nor museum collections (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9F7FFAFFE1FFB6D5FA3BCC6A04798C" author="Grazia J &amp; Panizzi AR &amp; Greve C &amp; Schwertner CF &amp; Campos LA &amp; Garbelotto TD &amp; Fernandes JA" box="[165,363,385,410]" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" pagination="681 - 756" refId="ref6851" refString="Grazia J, Panizzi AR, Greve C, Schwertner CF, Campos LA, Garbelotto TD, Fernandes JA. 2015. Stink Bugs (Pentatomidae). In: Panizzi AR, Grazia J, editors. True Bugs (Heteroptera) of the Neotropics (Entomology in Focus; 2). Springer, Dordrecht. p. 681 - 756." type="book chapter" year="2015">Grazia et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The literature is scarce on biological data about 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E7988FFE1FFB6D6FA3BCC6F49798C" baseAuthorityName="Germar" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[933,1062,385,410]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Ceratozygum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horridum">
<emphasis id="B97ADE19FFE1FFB6D6FA3BCC6F49798C" box="[933,1062,385,410]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="658">C. horridum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, lacking elementary information, e.g. specific host plants, vegetation strata of occurrence, preferences of specific parts of the host (i.e. stems, branches, leaves, or flowers), seasonal patterns, longevity. In the present study, field trips explored distinct ecoregions of 
<collectingCountry id="F319429BFFE1FFB6D5FF38416B857A33" box="[160,234,524,549]" name="Bolivia" pageId="9" pageNumber="658">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation id="C68C37B0FFE1FFB6D5A438416A3F7A33" box="[251,336,524,549]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="3.[160,216,142,165]" captionText="Table 1. Record data of Ceratozygum horridum and respective biomes and predictors values. TSMB: Tropical &amp; Subtropical Moist Broadleaf Forests; TSDB: Tropical &amp; Subtropical Dry Broadleaf Forests; *, ecotone between TSMB and TSDB. Elevation in metres above sea level. Ref.: 1 Castro-Huertas et al. 2015; 2; Kment and Vilímová 2010; 3; Packauskas and Schaefer 1998; 4 iNaturalist; 5 current study." pageId="9" pageNumber="658">Table 1</tableCitation>
), and despite the efforts, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E7988FFE1FFB6D7223841686F7A33" baseAuthorityName="Germar" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[637,768,524,549]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Ceratozygum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horridum">
<emphasis id="B97ADE19FFE1FFB6D7223841686F7A33" box="[637,768,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="658">C. horridum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens were sampled only in two locations with very low abundances. Thus, as far as we can infer, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E7988FFE1FFB6D6C438636F757A51" baseAuthorityName="Germar" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[923,1050,558,583]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Ceratozygum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="658" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horridum">
<emphasis id="B97ADE19FFE1FFB6D6C438636F757A51" box="[923,1050,558,583]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="658">C. horridum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in low densities across its distribution.
</paragraph>
